While Brexit was “the issue” it is also the symptom of the deeper philosophical conflict between “globalism” and “nationalism”. The common complaint of “traditional” labour voters was that they weren’t being listened to. “Nationalism” puts those same voters’ needs ahead of international globalist orthodoxy. It’s similar to Trump’s “Make America Great Again”.
The “globalist” reaction is to denegrate this appeal to be heard and characterise it as xenophobic and even racist. Continuing this attitude will doom labour to more failures. The question then to be answered is: can a compromise be reached between two fundamentally immiscible viewpoints?
